{
  "texts": [
    "However, when SCMs are incorporated in high proportions, a dilution effect may occur, which delays pozzolanic reactivity and results in reduced heat of hydration.",
    "Delaying the heat of hydration refers to the slowing down of the exothermic reaction between cement and water, resulting in reduced heat generation during the initial stages of hydration [30].",
    "This phenomenon often occurs when SCMs or additives are incorporated into the cement mix, altering the hydration kinetics.",
    "The delay can lead to reduced early heat release, extended setting times, and slower early strength development.",
    "However, it offers advantages such as preventing thermal cracking in massive concrete structures and minimizing the risk of rapid temperature rise in hot climates."
  ]
}